WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.360
My name is Brendan Graham and I am a data scientist at the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:09.920
And I'm really excited to talk to you all about a project I've been working on with a few colleagues

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:13.760
around how we're using machine learning to prevent patient harm in the hospital.

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:20.240
So to set the stage, every day thousands of tubes of blood make their way into the lab to be

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:25.280
analyzed. And these tubes of blood serve a really important purpose, which is to inform the care

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:31.200
of patients in the hospital. Clinicians need to make decisions about diagnoses, treatment plans,

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:36.799
and just monitor the status of their patients. And in the hallway in the fifth floor of the lab,

00:00:36.799 --> 00:00:42.480
there's a poster reminding us that behind every specimen, behind every tube of blood, is a patient.

00:00:43.599 --> 00:00:48.799
And oftentimes that's a sick patient. Let's call this patient John Smith. And John Smith's

00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:52.639
clinician is worried that he might have an infection, so they order some labs to check

00:00:52.639 --> 00:00:58.320
for it. So John Smith's blood is collected, put into a tube, it makes its way into the lab to be

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:04.720
analyzed. Somebody reviews those results, one of the lab technicians. Those results are then

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:09.519
published to the medical record, where they're accessed by the clinician caring for John Smith.

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:15.120
This forms kind of the typical life cycle of a blood test. But sometimes the wrong decision is

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:20.959
made, or the wrong treatment plan is implemented, and it's because there's wrong results in the chart.

00:01:20.959 --> 00:01:26.959
And those wrong results are not because that machine makes a mistake, and it's not a human

00:01:26.959 --> 00:01:32.959
error mistake by somebody reviewing their results. But rather, the wrong blood was put into the tube

00:01:32.959 --> 00:01:38.639
in the first place before it ever even got to the lab. And when that happens, this workflow looks

00:01:38.639 --> 00:01:43.040
something like this, where now there's a second patient in the mix. Let's call them Jane Smith.

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:48.239
And Jane Smith's blood was accidentally put into the tube labeled for John Smith.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:54.879
And once that happens, that tube proceeds along this pipeline, this workflow. And now we have the

00:01:54.879 --> 00:01:59.360
clinician making treatment decisions for John Smith based on the blood results for Jane Smith.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:05.839
And this is what's called a wrong blood in tube error, or a WIBIT. And as you can guess,

00:02:05.839 --> 00:02:11.039
the consequences of a WIBIT can be really severe. The wrong medications can be administered,

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:17.520
the decision not to administer a medication could be taken, and there could even be life-threatening

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:24.479
reactions from transfusion complications. To make this even more complicated or hard

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:29.839
of a problem to solve, these errors are often silent, meaning once the blood is put into the

00:02:29.839 --> 00:02:35.039
tube, there's nothing stopping the downstream processes from proceeding, right? It looks like

00:02:35.039 --> 00:02:40.479
blood in the tube, and everything can proceed as normal. And so this is a really potentially

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:45.360
difficult problem to detect, but potentially very severe in terms of patient harm and outcomes.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:51.679
But the goal of my talk is not to scare everybody. There are measures in place to

00:02:51.679 --> 00:02:56.800
prevent this from happening. So at the time of collection, there's a barcode scan that can happen.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:01.119
So on the wristband, there's a barcode. On the tube of blood, there's a barcode.

00:03:01.119 --> 00:03:04.639
Both are scanned at the time of collection to make sure that a mistake hasn't happened.

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:11.520
But human error, you can't account for everything, and so mistakes do end up happening.

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:16.960
So in the lab itself, there's an automated comparison that takes place. And lab machines

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:21.839
can perform what's called a single analyte delta check, which is really just a fancy way of saying,

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:26.320
let's take one component of the blood, one analyte, in this case, in this example,

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:31.279
a red blood cell count. So let's look at that analyte and compare it from the current sample

00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:36.160
from the patient to this previous sample from a patient over some short enough time frame.

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:40.399
And if the delta or the difference between those red blood cell counts is small enough,

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:44.240
then we can conclude that it's most likely the same patient sample, right? Over a short

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:47.679
enough time frame, certain characteristics of the blood shouldn't change too much.

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:55.119
And we were actually really interested in this automated approach because in the tubes of blood

00:03:55.119 --> 00:04:00.240
and in everybody's blood right now, there's more than just red blood cells, right? So we have

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:06.320
lymphocytes and monocytes and white blood cells and platelets and hemoglobin and all these different

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:11.759
components of the blood. So could we use all of them? Could we develop a multi-analyte approach

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:16.559
to detect wrong blood and tube errors using machine learning? Could we implement this in

00:04:16.559 --> 00:04:22.640
the clinical workflow to ultimately prevent patient harm from occurring? So with these goals in mind,

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:27.279
I'm going to talk through a project that I've been working on with a few colleagues in the labs

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:32.559
to do just this and some of the constraints that we came across and how we overcame them.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:39.279
So my job as the data scientist on the team is to start building up our data set. And we wanted

00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:45.119
to focus on complete blood count tests or CBCs. This is a very commonly used test in the hospital

00:04:45.119 --> 00:04:50.079
and all over. I would imagine everybody in this room has had a CBC test at some point, most likely.

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:58.239
And so I write some SQL code against our data warehouse and extract the results into a data

00:04:58.239 --> 00:05:04.880
frame in R to start the analysis. But we're now faced with the reality that the thing we're trying

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:10.880
to predict, these wibbits, there's no indicator in the data that flags when these happened.

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:17.760
As I mentioned before, these are silent errors. And it's almost impossible to go back retroactively

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:24.239
and understand in the data when a wibbit error has occurred. There's no logic we can implement

00:05:24.239 --> 00:05:29.760
that says if XYZ outcome occurs, it's always because a wibbit error happened that caused

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:35.920
that outcome. They're silent. And so we turned to a methodology in the literature that other

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:40.559
researchers have used, which is to simulate how a wibbit error might occur in practice.

00:05:41.359 --> 00:05:45.359
And before I kind of walk through that, I want to kind of orient everybody to what our data set

00:05:45.359 --> 00:05:51.359
really looked like. So before our simulation, we had in this fake data set here, we have

00:05:51.359 --> 00:05:56.239
columns for patient ID and when the collection was taken. So when the specimens were taken,

00:05:57.119 --> 00:06:01.519
we also have the actual results from the blood test. So white blood cell count, red blood cell

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:08.559
count, a dozen and a half other results. Then for every sample, for every patient, we grab their

00:06:08.559 --> 00:06:13.200
previous sample, right? And we get their previous results. And then we take the difference between

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:17.200
those two results across all of the analytes. Remember, this is our multi-analyte approach.

00:06:18.799 --> 00:06:23.279
And these analytes, sorry, these deltas actually form the predictors in the model.

00:06:24.239 --> 00:06:29.600
So we have our predictors, but we don't have an outcome. So to simulate these outcomes in a way

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:34.000
that kind of approximates how they occur in practice, we use the matching algorithm from

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.000
the matchit package that matched temporally and on department. So if we have a patient in our

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:45.600
data set in the neonatal ICU, the NICU, what we want to do is find another patient in the NICU

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:51.119
who had their sample taken around the same time. And then once we have a match, we overwrite the

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:56.399
results of one patient with the matched patient. And we kind of introduce a synthetic wibbit error.

00:06:56.399 --> 00:07:01.359
And that looks something like this. So we have, let's say we ran our algorithm on this fake data

00:07:01.359 --> 00:07:07.040
set and we've matched patient 1, 2, 3 with patient 7, 8, 9, because they had their samples collected

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:10.799
only a half hour apart. And let's say, for the sake of example, they're in the same department.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:16.799
We take the results from patient 7, 8, 9 and overwrite the original results of patient 1,

00:07:16.799 --> 00:07:22.720
2, 3. And then when we take the deltas, we can see that specifically the white blood cell count delta

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:28.399
in the simulated data set is 9.7 compared to 1.6 in sort of the unmodified data set.

00:07:28.399 --> 00:07:32.880
So we've introduced this wibbit error, which is reflected in this really high delta,

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:40.160
which allows us to create a new column or wibbit indicator column. And this approach,

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:46.640
we repeated for our entire data set. And it took us in this kind of stylized example here,

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:52.959
on the left, of a situation where we had, you know, no wibbits in our data set to running it on

00:07:52.959 --> 00:07:57.839
our 50% of the samples and finding a match. And now we have like a perfectly balanced data set

00:07:57.839 --> 00:08:03.200
in terms of the outcome, which is great for model training. But, you know, keep this in the back of

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:06.239
your mind, because as we talk about model assessment, this is going to play a pretty

00:08:06.239 --> 00:08:12.239
big role in how we assess our models. But speaking of models, we move on to doing some modeling. And

00:08:12.239 --> 00:08:16.320
so we want to develop a binary classification model, right, like a wibbit or no wibbit.

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:20.880
And so using the tidy models framework, which I would imagine lots of people are familiar with,

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:26.320
this was incredibly easy. We have a couple different types of models ranging in the

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:30.399
complexity, a couple different types of preprocessing and predictor sets that we're

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:35.760
thinking about using. And using kind of this high level example code on the left there,

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:41.119
mainly the workflow map function from tidy models really allowed us to pretty easily

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:47.840
work through training and, you know, validating all these different kind of combinations. And

00:08:48.719 --> 00:08:52.479
the full technical like details of the modeling, it's kind of out of scope for this talk. I'm not

00:08:52.479 --> 00:08:56.719
going to get too into the weeds, but if you are interested, feel free to stop me. I'd be happy to

00:08:56.719 --> 00:09:02.719
talk about it some more. So we're at the point now where we have our models, we have our data,

00:09:02.719 --> 00:09:06.640
and we train our models using cross-validation, and we want to see how do the models perform.

00:09:07.359 --> 00:09:13.440
So here I have some ROC curves for the two different CBC test subtypes. And if you're

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:18.320
unfamiliar with ROC curves, basically like the curves towards the upper left of all the plots

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:23.760
are performing better in terms of ROC. And the colors here represent the different model types

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:29.359
and preprocessing combinations. So we can see kind of a range of performance profiles in terms of ROC

00:09:29.359 --> 00:09:35.359
curves, but the best models performed extremely well, which, you know, wasn't too surprising.

00:09:35.359 --> 00:09:41.599
We have this like simulated data, we've injected these errors, and it's not surprising that the

00:09:41.599 --> 00:09:46.159
predictors have a lot of information about when a WIBIT error occurs because we've overwritten

00:09:46.159 --> 00:09:52.239
the results with a different patient. So it's not totally surprising, but also, you know,

00:09:52.239 --> 00:09:56.559
this isn't just a model development exercise. We're not just concerned with the fact that

00:09:57.119 --> 00:10:01.119
it's cool to make models with nice data. We actually want to think about implementing this,

00:10:01.119 --> 00:10:05.919
right? Like who could use these models and how would they use them in their workflow?

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:12.479
What happens if we get a prediction wrong? And so this kind of switched our mindset from

00:10:12.479 --> 00:10:16.880
like model development. Like I said, we're not just concerned with developing classification

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:21.599
models, but how do we implement these into the clinical workflow? And so we kind of switched

00:10:21.599 --> 00:10:27.919
gears into the clinical workflow and faced a new set of constraints, specifically around

00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:34.320
false positives. So here I have on the screen kind of the classic confusion matrix, a two-by-two

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:40.239
table comparing predicted versus actual values. And on the top row, we have true positives and

00:10:40.239 --> 00:10:45.359
false positives. Bottom row, we have false negatives and true negatives. And the false

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:49.919
positives are highlighted for an important reason, because you can think about a hypothetical

00:10:49.919 --> 00:10:54.880
scenario in the future where we have this model in production and we make a prediction. We see

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:59.280
a sample and we think, oh, this is a wibbit. So now we're kind of living in that top row. We're

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:04.799
either correct, it's a true positive, or we've made a prediction and it's a false positive. It's

00:11:04.799 --> 00:11:09.679
not a real wibbit. And in the context of like the clinical lab, the false positive translates to a

00:11:09.679 --> 00:11:14.400
lot of extra work that somebody now has to do. They probably have to rerun that test to make

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:20.640
sure that they get the same weird result, which delays all the other tests in line and which has

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:24.400
downstream impacts on all those patients and the clinicians waiting for those results.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:32.080
They might have to find the ordering provider, call them, get in touch with them somehow, and

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:37.679
say, hey, did you really order this blood test for John Smith? Because there have been anecdotal

00:11:37.679 --> 00:11:42.400
evidence in the past where you get a blood result published in the chart and the provider says,

00:11:42.400 --> 00:11:46.320
I never ordered this. And so one quick way to check for a wibbit is just confirming, hey, did

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:52.239
you actually order this for this patient? Again, that's extra work on the backs of the lab staff.

00:11:53.119 --> 00:11:57.599
And at the scale that the CHOP lab operates, it has real impacts on turnaround time and just

00:11:57.599 --> 00:12:04.400
overall lab efficiency. So it's something we want to avoid. Another idea that's been floating in

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:09.359
the back of our minds here is around this idea of alert fatigue. So people who work in kind of

00:12:09.359 --> 00:12:14.239
a clinical capacity, whether they're on the front lines or kind of like in the background as the lab

00:12:14.239 --> 00:12:20.239
staff are, they're bombarded with medical device beepings and PA going off and pagers going off. And

00:12:20.239 --> 00:12:24.479
even in the software itself, there's alerts popping up reminding them to do something.

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:29.280
And what we're kind of talking about here is making another alert telling them to do something.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
So the last thing we want to do is have that alert firing a lot unnecessarily.

00:12:35.039 --> 00:12:41.119
So with these two kind of ideas in mind, we were thinking as we move to evaluate the models,

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:47.679
maybe we should move on from focusing on more of the traditional classification metrics like

00:12:48.799 --> 00:12:53.119
accuracy and ROC that I showed earlier and think about positive predictive value,

00:12:53.919 --> 00:12:59.359
which is the proportion of all positives that are true positives. And so if we can have a model or

00:12:59.359 --> 00:13:04.640
identify a model that has a high positive predictive value, we can be as confident as we

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:09.760
can that when we raise an alert, that it will hopefully not result in a lot of unnecessary

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:13.440
extra work. I mean, there will always be false positives, but we can try our best to reduce that.

00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:19.119
One of the potential issues that we ran into, or not potential issue, an issue that we ran into

00:13:19.119 --> 00:13:24.479
with this though, is that PPV is extremely sensitive to the prevalence of the outcome.

00:13:25.119 --> 00:13:29.440
And if you remember a few slides ago, when I talked about how we took our training data and

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:36.799
made it kind of perfectly balanced in this nice bar charts here on the left, this will have major

00:13:36.799 --> 00:13:43.359
implications if we were to assess our models with the holdout data, with data the models

00:13:43.359 --> 00:13:49.359
haven't seen yet, that if it's structured the same way, we would vastly overestimate the prevalence

00:13:49.359 --> 00:13:55.280
of the outcome. We would probably overestimate the model PPV. And that has, like I said,

00:13:55.280 --> 00:14:02.159
real-world implications for generating a lot of false positives. So to help get over this constraint,

00:14:03.119 --> 00:14:09.599
we chose to downsample in the holdout data set, the wibbit proportions, such that, excuse me,

00:14:09.599 --> 00:14:14.159
the wibbit prevalence in our holdout data set matched the real-world, excuse me, prevalence of

00:14:14.159 --> 00:14:22.239
the wibbits that are reported in the literature. And the real-world, the reported prevalence is

00:14:22.239 --> 00:14:27.679
like one in 3,000 to one in 5,000 samples. So it's pretty low. So what that means for us,

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:34.000
like practically in our data set, is that we have about 11,000 or so samples in the holdout data set

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:40.479
and we downsample them so that only three wibbits remain out of 11,000. So the idea is to like

00:14:40.479 --> 00:14:47.039
unleash the models on this unbalanced, downsampled, low-prevalence validation data set and then see

00:14:47.039 --> 00:14:53.119
how the models perform in terms of PPV. Another thing to think about though, as we assess the

00:14:53.119 --> 00:15:01.359
models, is what's the threshold that we want to raise an alert at? You know, the default 50%

00:15:01.359 --> 00:15:06.880
threshold is probably too low. It might generate a lot of false positives. But what is the optimal

00:15:06.880 --> 00:15:13.840
threshold? Is it 90%, 95%? We don't know that right now. It's not obvious. And so using the

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:19.599
model validation data set, we actually use the probability package to iterate across a bunch of

00:15:19.599 --> 00:15:24.880
different probability thresholds and then reassessed the model performance at each

00:15:24.880 --> 00:15:30.640
threshold, again on this unbalanced, low-prevalence validation data set, which looked something like

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:39.200
this. So if we used, again in this unbalanced data set, using a probability threshold of 0.95,

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:47.840
we have 61 false positives and a PPV of 0.05, which is pretty low, even at this high threshold.

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:52.799
And which makes sense, we have a really low prevalent outcome. But one of our goals here was

00:15:52.799 --> 00:15:57.840
to see how high could we push this threshold while still capturing those three true positives that we

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:02.640
know are in our validation data set. And so again, using this probability package, we're able to

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:08.080
iterate across thresholds. Here, we're bringing it up to 0.99. We see a reduction in the false

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:16.239
positives and a slight increase in PPV to just under 0.09. And as we increase the threshold even

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:23.599
more, we see that same pattern. We see fewer false positives and a PPV of about 0.21, which again

00:16:23.599 --> 00:16:30.400
is pretty modest. But given the low prevalence of this outcome, we were actually pretty happy with

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:35.119
this. And actually, if we increase the threshold even higher, we start to drop one of those three

00:16:35.119 --> 00:16:40.400
true positives. And that validates one of the criteria that we really care about, which is

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:44.559
making sure that we can flag the ones that we know exist in our holdout data set.

00:16:46.159 --> 00:16:53.440
Another positive kind of unintended effect of this kind of analysis is it helped to frame

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:59.520
the discussion at, let's say, higher levels, like hospital administration levels, on the trade-off

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:04.719
of maybe implementing a model like this, which we know there will be false positives. We know

00:17:04.719 --> 00:17:10.640
there will be some unnecessary work. But we also hope that we prevent unnecessary patient

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:15.439
harm from occurring if we're able to catch a WIBIT error. So there's a trade-off there.

00:17:15.439 --> 00:17:19.520
And this sort of analysis across these thresholds can at least help inform that discussion

00:17:20.239 --> 00:17:27.119
on that exact trade-off of what we estimate the false positive rate to be and the benefit of

00:17:27.119 --> 00:17:31.199
potentially catching these WIBIT errors. Again, this kind of in the future as we think about

00:17:31.199 --> 00:17:38.560
implementation. And speaking of implementation, over the next few months, we plan to dive deeper

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:44.239
into this to figure out how does a model API that lives on our Kinect server interface with the lab

00:17:44.239 --> 00:17:48.239
middleware, that machine that does the analysis? Because the model needs to know, hey, a test is

00:17:48.239 --> 00:17:53.680
ready to bring you to check. And then if we make a prediction and we need to raise an error,

00:17:54.640 --> 00:18:01.760
we may need to point that API or that alert to the EMR software. And somebody has to see that,

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:06.319
which is another system. And then maybe a lab technician has to have an alert pop up or a

00:18:06.319 --> 00:18:12.079
front-end provider. So we're really excited to kind of dive into this next set of constraints

00:18:12.079 --> 00:18:16.000
that we hope we can overcome and implement this in the workflow and get all these things talking.

00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:20.319
Because as I mentioned before, even though this is a low prevalence outcome,

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:25.680
it's an instance of preventable patient harm. And this is that poster. I took the picture of

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:30.079
it in the hallway in the lab. Behind every one of those tubes of blood, there's a patient and

00:18:30.079 --> 00:18:34.880
their family and their providers who are kind of all counting on this process to go right.

00:18:35.439 --> 00:18:41.119
And we hope that by hopefully implementing these models, we'll be able to kind of deliver on that.

00:18:41.199 --> 00:18:42.079
So thank you.

00:18:51.199 --> 00:18:56.959
I think we have time for probably a few questions. Do you have problems with true

00:18:56.959 --> 00:19:00.640
whippets that you didn't simulate in your training data introducing noise into your model?

00:19:01.599 --> 00:19:06.400
For sure we do, but it's hard to know exactly where they are. That's kind of the whole crux

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:12.400
of the problem. So yes, the data is noisy for sure in ways that it's hard to account for.

00:19:15.119 --> 00:19:18.880
And how do you avoid error in a first-time visit or single blood collection,

00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:20.719
for example, like an outpatient?

00:19:20.719 --> 00:19:25.359
Yeah. Good question. So a few inclusion criteria that I did not mention was that we're only

00:19:25.359 --> 00:19:29.359
focused on inpatients, number one, because that error is more likely to occur in an inpatient

00:19:29.359 --> 00:19:34.400
setting than if you're just coming into an office visit. And as far as patients who don't have a

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:39.359
previous sample, one of the inclusion criteria that we used was that a patient had to have a

00:19:39.359 --> 00:19:46.079
CBC within the last seven days. So in an inpatient setting, that's not too restrictive, but there

00:19:46.079 --> 00:19:49.520
does have to be a sample within some relative timeframe for you to take that difference.

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:55.119
And it has to be kind of short enough so that there's not like a change in the blood,

00:19:55.119 --> 00:19:59.359
especially with younger patients, like infants and like a couple of day-old patients, they have,

00:19:59.359 --> 00:20:02.560
they can fluctuate a lot. So we have to keep that timeframe pretty short.

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:05.599
Okay. I think that's all the time that we have, but thank you so much.

00:20:05.599 --> 00:20:05.680
Thank you.

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:10.160
And thanks to all of our other speakers as well.

